        "timestamp": "2020-01-14 13:51:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review\n\n> > Patch Set 2:\n > >\n > > (2 comments)\n > >\n > > I tend to think that 2 root images are best.   One, lightweight\n > for the use of api/pap/distribution/pdp-x as lighter weight\n > components.   The openjdk jre over ubuntu buster slim is sufficient\n > for it.\n > >\n > > The other one, with the openjdk 11 + maven, heavier weight for\n > the drools pdp, policy engine perhaps (as I think brmsgw needs it\n > to deploy artifacts, sometimes maven in this image used to deal\n > with maven deploy problems as well) , and perhaps apex.  I don't\n > think there is a new for the policy-base one, I think it can easily\n > be integrated into the other 2, it doesn't offer much benefit.\n > >\n > > As I noted below, I would prefer to use the official maven image\n > as the base for the second image, as it is official, and would be\n > maintained by other folks, and we could just reuse.\n > \n > I'm ok with this strategy - Jim? Liam/Ram - does Apex need maven?\n\nWorks for me - I had wondered why we had these two.  Maybe I'll replace them with policy-debian-jre and policy-debian-maven, instead, where the latter will be based off of the jdk.\n\nI should note, however, that I think I was unable to get maven to install via \"apt\" even starting with a vanilla debian-slim or alpine image; there was something wrong with the openjdk11 headless jre on which it depends.  However, I can change it to download from apache instead of osu, like the csit scripts do.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
